s in\nthe temperature range $10^5<T<10^7$ K has also been calculated. We show that of\nthe total background, (1) no more than 2% comes from the region with\ntemperature less than $10^{6.5}$ K, and (2) no more than 7% is from the region\nof dark matter with mass density $\\rho_{\\rm dm}<50 \\bar{\\rho}_{\\rm dm}$. The\nregion of $\\rho_{\\rm dm}>50\\bar{\\rho}_{\\rm dm}$ is generally clustered and\ndiscretely distributed. Therefore, almost all of the soft X-ray background\ncomes from clustered sources, and the contribution from truly diffuse gas is\nprobably negligible. This point agrees with current X-ray observations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 9 Jan 2006 21:36:55 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 9 May 2006 17:59:49 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-11"}
